Simulated Patient Readmission Data

This simulation builds on a semi-simulated dataset of hospital readmission data from diabetes patients.

The dataset given is a largescale semi-simulated dataset that was created from published data regarding hospital readmission rates for diabetic patients. The analytical features which appear in the data were engineered from a variety of additional simulated data sources. These included grocery purchases (to estimate the percentage calories from carbohydrates in a patients diet) and wearable vital sign sensor data (to quantify activity).

We were asked to extend this project by adding a genetic confounder to the dataset in order to simulate Simpsons Paradox.

Confounding the effect of the percentage of calories from carbs

The coefficient of percentage of calories from carbs is positive (about 0.52), meaning that probability of readmission goes up with higher percentage calories from carbs. We want to design a confounder so the coefficient of calories comes out negative; that is, within each genetic group, the probability of readmission should go down as a patients percentage calories from carbs goes up.

We will use the same approach our project sponsor, Bob Horton, used in his blog post on simulating Simpsons Paradox through confounders (http://blog.revolutionanalytics.com/2015/11/fun-with-simpsons-paradox-simulating-confounders.html).

To do so, we need to use a continuous variable which corresponds to the probability of being readmitted in regard to a patients percent calories from carbs.

Below, we create the variable readmission_score in order to assign numerical scores to the categorical variable readmitted.

plot( pct_calories_from_carbs ~ readmitted, data=pts)

The plot above displays a scatterplot of the patients readmission scores in regard to their percent calories from carbohydrates.

Next, we will group these points into a set of parallel stripes with slopes which go in the opposite direction of the general trend from the scatterplot above.

Drawing Stripes

point_line_distance <- function(b, m, x, y)
  (y - (m*x + b))/sqrt(m^2 + 1)

confounded_data_frame <- function(x, y, m, num_grp){
  b <- 0 # intercept doesn't matter
  d <- point_line_distance(b, m, x, y)
  d_scaled <- 0.0005 + 0.999 * (d - min(d))/(max(d) - min(d)) # avoid 0 and 1
  data.frame(x=x, y=y, 
             group=as.factor(sprintf("grp%02d", ceiling(num_grp*(d_scaled)))))
}
numGroups <- 25
rbow <- rainbow(numGroups, end=2/3)
confounded <- confounded_data_frame(pts$pct_calories_from_carbs, pts$readmission_score, -4.10, numGroups)
pts$group <- confounded$group

with(pts, plot(readmission_score ~ pct_calories_from_carbs, 
               col=rbow[as.integer(group)], 
               pch=as.integer(readmitted),
               cex=0.75))

fit <- glm(readmit30 ~ group:pct_calories_from_carbs, pts, family=binomial(link="logit"))

After taking a look at the density plots and frequency tables for each group, we dedcided that group 16 would be an excellent group to use as our genetic confounder because it has a good amount ofoverlap in patients who were readmitted within 30 days and those who were readmitted after 30 days. By confounding this group, it would be plausible to argue that there is another factor playing a role in a patients likelihood to be readmitted within the first 30 days of being discharged in regard to the amount of calories from carbohydrates they consume.

We chose the gene IRS1 to use as our genetic confounder. Mutations in this gene have been reported to have a role in determining susceptibility traits related to type 2 diabetes. We choose its RR allele to act as our confounder, is it is the rarest genotype for this gene. Because the confounded stripe is only roughly 1/25th of the data, it makes sense to assign this allele to it. For the sake of simplicity, we assign the other two alleles such that all of the patients in the groups preceding group 16 have the GG allele and those following group 16 have the GR allele.

Assigning the alleles to the groups

irs1 <- rep("GR", nrow(pts))
pts[["irs1"]] <- irs1
pts$irs1 <- ifelse(pts$group == "grp16", "RR", pts$irs1)

for (i in 1:9) {
  groupName <- paste("grp0", i, sep="")
  pts$irs1 <- ifelse(pts$group == groupName, "GG", pts$irs1)
}

for (i in 0:5) {
  groupName <- paste("grp1", i, sep="")
  pts$irs1 <- ifelse(pts$group == groupName, "GG", pts$irs1)
}

pts$irs1 <- as.factor(pts$irs1)

Now that we have assigned an allele to each patient, lets take another look at the same scatterplot from before. This time, colored by a patients IRS1 allele, rather than readmission score.

The green stripe in the scatterplot above clearly shows a confounding relationship between the IRS1 RR allele and a patients probability of readmission in regard to the amount of calories from carbohydrates they consume.

Now that we have a dataset which contains this confounding relationship, we can create a new dataset which only contains the simulated features we used earlier (in our first linear model) along with the new IRS1 column. This new dataset can be used to analyze the effects these features may have on a diabetic patients probability of being readmitted within the first 30 days. Readmission score would not be included in the new data set since these are pseudo data simulated into the
